rk fine.  Louis, in contrast, has installed the system version of\n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":" as a primitive for the metacircular\n    evaluator.  When he tries it, things go terribly wrong.  Explain why\n    Louis's ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"map"},{"body":" fails even though\n    Eva's works.\n    ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-1","count":1,"href":"/sicpjs/4.1.4#footnote-link-1","child":[{"body":"Any\n    function\n    defined in the underlying\n    Python\n    can be used as a primitive for the metacircular evaluator.  The name of a\n    primitive installed in the evaluator need not be the same as the name of its\n    implementation in the underlying\n    Python\n    the names are the same here because the metacircular evaluator implements\n    Python    \n    itself.\n    Thus, for example, we could put \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"llist(\"first\", head)"},{"body":" \n    or \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"llist(\"square\", x => x * x)"},{"body":"\n    in the list of \n    ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"primitive_functions"},{"body":".\n      ","tag":"#text"}]},{"tag":"DISPLAYFOOTNOTE","id":"#footnote-2","count":2,"href":"/sicpjs/4.1.4#footnote-link-2","child":[{"body":"\n        Python's ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"apply"},{"body":" method \n\texpects the function arguments in a ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"EM","child":[{"body":"vector","tag":"#text"}]},{"body":". (Vectors\n\tare called \"","tag":"#text"},{"body":"arrays","tag":"#text"},{"body":"\" in Python.)\n\tThus, the ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"arglist"},{"body":" is transformed into \n        a\n\t\n\tvector—here using a while\n\tloop (see exercise ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"4.7","href":"/sicpjs/4.1.2#ex-4.7"},{"body":"):\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"SNIPPET","latex":true,"eval":false,"body":"\ndef apply_in_underlying_javascript(prim, arglist):\n    arg_vector = []\n    # empty vector\n    i = 0\n    while  not is_none(arglist):\n        arg_vector[i] = head(arglist)\n        # store value at index $\\texttt{i}$\n        i = i + 1\n        arglist = tail(arglist)\n    return prim.apply(prim, arg_vector)\n    # $\\texttt{apply}$ is accessed via $\\texttt{prim}$\n"},{"body":"\n\tWe also made use of\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"apply_in_underlying_javascript"},{"body":"\n\tto declare the function\n\t","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"PYTHONINLINE","body":"apply_generic"},{"body":"\n\tin section ","tag":"#text"},{"tag":"REF","body":"2.4.3","href":"/sicpjs/2.4.3"},{"body":".\n      ","tag":"#text"}]}]